        "paragraph_index": 5,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe Cd²⁺–Cl⁻ system is notable for its **moderate but non-trivial chloro-complex formation** — log β₁ = 1.32 is much weaker than, say, Cd²⁺–EDTA (log β ≈ 16), but strong enough to be environmentally significant. In seawater and chloride-rich groundwaters, a substantial fraction of dissolved Cd²⁺ exists as CdCl⁺ and CdCl₂, which dramatically affects its bioavailability and toxicity. The fact that β₃ > β₄ (log β drops from 1.80 to 1.46 for the fourth chloride) reflects steric crowding in the tetrachloro complex. The remarkable consistency of the recommended value across 38 compilation editions spanning ~40 years underscores the robustness of the original Schwarzenbach & Ackermann measurement.",
